      "source": "# Conclusion",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "\n# In this assignment, different machine learning models and ensemble learning\n# techniques were used to predict accommodation affordability. The dataset was\n# divided into training and testing data using train_test_split so that the\n# models could be evaluated fairly on unseen data.\n\n# Logistic Regression was first used as the baseline model and achieved an\n# accuracy of 79.28%. This model performed reasonably well, but because it is\n# a linear model, it may not fully capture complicated patterns in the dataset.\n\n# GaussianNB achieved the lowest accuracy of 75.32%. This could be because\n# GaussianNB assumes that features are independent from each other, which is\n# usually not true in real-world datasets. The lower accuracy suggests that\n# the accommodation features may have stronger relationships with each other.\n\n# DecisionTreeClassifier achieved a much higher accuracy of 85.81%.\n# Decision trees are able to learn nonlinear relationships and more complex\n# patterns in the data. This result suggests that the dataset contains patterns\n# that are better handled by tree-based models than by simple linear models.\n\n# The VotingClassifier achieved an accuracy of 82.76%. Hard voting combines\n# predictions from multiple models and chooses the majority prediction.\n# The voting classifier performed better than GaussianNB and Logistic Regression,\n# but slightly lower than DecisionTreeClassifier. This may be because weaker\n# models affected the final voting decision.\n\n# The StackingClassifier achieved an accuracy of 85.82%, which was one of the\n# best results in the assignment. Stacking combines different models together\n# and uses another model to learn the best way to combine predictions.\n# This helped improve overall performance because the strengths of multiple\n# models were combined.\n\n# BaggingClassifier achieved the highest accuracy of 87.92%.\n# Bagging works by training multiple decision trees on random subsets of the\n# dataset and combining their predictions. This helps reduce overfitting and\n# improves model stability. The high accuracy shows that bagging was very\n# effective for this dataset.\n\n# AdaBoostClassifier achieved an accuracy of 83.56%.\n# Boosting improves performance by focusing more on incorrectly classified\n# observations during training. Although the model performed well, it did not\n# perform as strongly as Bagging and Stacking on this dataset.\n\n# Overall, the results show that ensemble learning methods generally perform\n# better than single models because they combine the strengths of multiple\n# learners. Bagging and Stacking produced the best results, showing that\n# ensemble methods are very useful when dealing with datasets that contain\n# complex relationships and patterns.",
